tspan.tspan: The other agencies have abilities that you lack, you will probably need
their help, but they have their own desires as well, so figuring out how to
get them to help isn't always simple. Some characters will even
threaten your existence, but you will find that there's always a better
deal you can make with them than war.
You may wish to try playing with, or without, a contract system, wherein
players can make agreements to take a -10 point punishments if a
specified condition occurs. For example, if you wanted me to do
something for you, you could pledge to do something in return, or else
face a penalty.

games they played is above par for their current level, they transcend to
the next level.

tspan.tspan: The play objective is to pursue your character's desires and optimize
the
world towards perfection. The real objective, which comes as a
result of
pursuing the play objective, is to practice negotiation
in a
lawless place,
to learn to weave harmony amid exposed difference.
The play objective is to pursue your character's desires and optimize
the world as far as you can. The real objective is to practice
negotiation
in a lawless place, to weave shared plans amid conflict.
It's rare in life that we deliberately practice Negotiation, and yet our skill in it determines so much.
It's
needed whenever there's disagreement, power, collective decisions to be made, it essentially is
the
core skill of Politics, even Love needs it. But so dire and abberant are the situations from which
it
emerges that in its natural form, it is not fun. So we avoid it, we don't train, and becase we're all so
inept in it, terrible things happen, wars, and all the lesser tragedies of daily social life.
P1 aims to provide a special space where practicing negotiation can be fun.
It primarily does this by being a game, as opposed to most other opportunities we get to negotiate,
which are not games. Genuine real life dramas often make poor learning experiences, punishing
repeated trial and explorative strategies with permanent injuries, demanding avoidance and
conservatism and forbidding experimentation. Games are places where experimentation is safe and
easy. It also helps for a game to be very transparent: The actions and goals of all of the players are
simple and clear, so when the game ends, the significance of whatever happened can easily be
interpreted and learned from.
There are no other games like this. There are lots of reasons for that. We don't think any of them are
serious. On the other side of our labor you will (eventually) find a genre of games that are much
richer.
Cohabitive games are able to model a much wider variety of characters, relationships, and
stories
than purely competitive or purely cooperative games can.

The Fable of the Parasitic Centipede
An intrepid young wolf was out in search of its place in
the world, then, without any warning, a horrible parasitic
centipede dropped out of a tree, landed on the wolf's
back, and latched on with every one of its barbed legs.
It hurt, and it hurt more when the wolf scratched at it.
The centipede said "If you try to remove me again, I will
sting you with venom, and kill you", so the wolf stopped
scratching, and the pain stopped. The wolf and the
centipede had a patient character, so as soon as the
wolf
accepted that the centipede could not be removed,
the
two became friends.
The wolf and the parasitic centipede had many
interesting conversations. The centipede could tell the
wolf about where tasty grubs lived in rotted trees, and it
was true, and the wolf found them and ate them, and the
centipede enjoyed their flavor in the
wolf's blood. The
wolf and the parasitic centipede
enjoyed the grubs
together.
Eventually the wolf found a perfect tree for the parasitic
centipede to lay its eggs in, and so after all of their
travels, it was time for the parasitic centipede to leave
the wolf, and the centipede observed, "When I let go, I
wont be able to sting you any more." The wolf answered.
"Of course. I will be pleased with that." The centipede
asked, "But that means you could chase me and stomp
on me." And the wolf answered, "You've been honorable.
I will not hurt you. It's safe to let go." And the centipede
could feel in its feet that it was true.
So the centipede pried up its many barbed feet out of
the
wolf's back, jumped away. The wolf stood and
watched it
crawl along the ground, and noticed that the
centipede
had become enormous in the time after it had
first
attached, it now looked more like a giant caterpillar.
The
centipede safely reached its tree, and laid many
eggs in
it, which grew into new centipedes, who
eventually found
their own wolves, and the cycle
continued.
Eventually, cycle after cycle, after a million years,
wolves
learned to use centipedes and their venom
during their
hunts, and
centipede was allowed to live in
wolf's den.
Wolf and
centipede could no longer imagine
living apart.
